fix rounding issue in unwind() (#1)

* fix rounding issue in unwind()
debt (art*rate) is being rounded down to full units of DAI when
repaying, this can cause the repayment to _sometimes_ fail.

The reason it does not always fail is because the GUniLev contract
will pitch in using its vat.dai() dust balance to repay the loan
(often that is sufficient to cover the fractional amount "lost" by
rounding down).

- add a test that sets the vat.dai(lev) balance to zero to force a
  repayment failure during unwind
- change the rounding used by unwind() such that it rounds up instead
  of down, this only affects the flashloan amount

* fix whitespace

Suggestions (#3)

* Remove underscore suffix in events

* Save storage read in build(), inline salt().

Saves 139 gas.

* Inline code().

Saves 43 gas.

* Upgrade to solc 0.8.11

Saves 128 gas on execute, 3775 on build.

* Align undescores for calldata and local vars.

To avoid calldata collision with storage - undescore is suffix.
To avoid loval var collision with storage - undescore is prefix.

* Change require message to claimer-proxy-already-exists.

The previous message proxy-registered-to-owner was a bit confusing, as
it is not clear if proxy is the new proxy or the old proxy.

Also owner was a bit ambiguous since it is not guaranteed that owner parameter
is the msg.sender (there is a check for that beforehand but someone just
seeing the require message might not neccesarily know that).

* Fix CI

* claimer -> owner

tokemak's new staking contract(s).

* (re)tTOKE -> (re)TOKE and now a share token rather than being 1:1 pegged
* shares are distributed upon deposit, and not with fills
  * this is solved by introducing a penalty when depositing
* a migration function that moves over all the tokens from the previous contract
* the vault is now a proxy contract, more specifically, a UUPS and ERC-1967 interface
* there's no deadline, the vault is now cycle-dependent
* withdrawals needs to be requested before withdrawals are possible
* partially implements the ERC-4626 interface

Update Smart Contracts based on Solidified Audit

Issues:

[1] Ownable contract does not implement a function to revoke access;

Added a `removeOwnership(address allowedAddress)` method to revoke
ownership access. Includes a new event `RevokeOwnership`

[2] Beware of possible collisions in TokenIOStorage;

Reviewed instances where this occurs. There is not an immediate upgrade
to the contracts to check whether a conflict occurs for an issuer. Doing
so would require a check across all issued assets. Handling this issue
may best be suited for UI at the time of authorizing a new firm.

[3] Use of hard coded constants;

Removed all instances of the hard coded "feeMsg" and added it as a
parameter to the TokenIoFeeContract. Now feeContracts can include a
default fee message for transactions that include additional fees (e.g.
for wire transfers, merchants, etc.)

This feeMsg is also able to be set as part of the `setFeeParams()` method.
It is also included in the getFeeParams() method

[4] SafeMath is outdated;

Replaces instances of `assert()` with `require()` to avoid consuming
entire transaction gas

[5] Consider locking version pragma

Locked all version pragma to 0.4.24;

[6] Use of experimental features;

Removed use of experimental features per recommendation of audit

[7] Incorrect constructor comments

Fixed inaccurate constructor comments for contract names

[8] TODO: Consider including messages in require() statements

This is yet to be added, but will be included in a subsequent commit.

Cdp Registry + Roll in Proxy Actions (#24)

* Add CDP registry

* Tests pass

* Fix comment for mapping

* Add roll proxy action

* Embed cdp owner in internal functions parameters.

This is to remove requires at the beginning of functions as much as possible.
Note that any action must check/pass both the owner and the ilk (otherwise
caller can use an ambigous cdp number, which is a UX problem).

Note that this change still doesn't support cdp delegation
(i.e using cdpAllow). For that more changes are needed such as adding move
and flux operations (and more).

* Small interface changes to align to regular proxy-actions

Also moving to use owner instead of address(this) in a few more places.
Note that delegation is still not supported.

List of changes from regular proxy-actions:
* based on dev branch (not deployed yet).
* assuming address(this) = = owner.
* _ethJoin_join and _gemJoin_join are internal (since we decided they are
  not needed externally).
* give, giveToProxy do not exist (since no cdp manager).
* cdpAllow, urnAllow do not exist (since delegation not supported yet).
* flux, move, frob do not exist (since we decided they are not needed).
* enter, shift do not exist (since fork is not supported in charter).
* safeWipe, safeWipeAll do not exist (since currently owner has to be
  address(this)).
* no unpermissioned paths in wipe and wipeall (as assumming address(this)==owner).

* Add CdpRegistry test

* wipe() - use owner local var

Switch to a more permissive verification check.

EIP-3074 has two versions, which I'll refer to as "strong" and "weak".
In the strong version, which is the currently specified version,
`tx.origin` is allowed to equal `msg.sender` after an `AUTHCALL`. This
is the preferred version of the EIP, but does possibly introduce some
minor problems for exceeding rare cases.

The "weak" version, on the other hand, does not allow `tx.origin` to
equal `msg.sender`.

This commit will allow the "weak" version of EIP-3074 to unlock the
bribes.
